<h2>Atlas <span class="subtitle">— the enliterated collection, drawn</span></h2>

<p class="muted" style="max-width:62rem">
  Every record the heartbeat has read is a node; every claim that names something — an advisor,
  an agency, a superseded order, a related report — is a typed edge. The edge types ARE the
  controlled vocabulary, and every edge carries its provenance: hover a line to see who asserted
  it, when, at what confidence, and the audit verdict where one exists. The overview starts with
  context regions and bridge topics; Explore opens the capped graph; Focus follows a selected
  node's neighborhood.
</p>

<%= render "viewer", atlas: nil, embedded: false, data_url: @atlas_data_url %>

<p class="muted samples" style="margin-top:.6rem">
  Entities are deduped by exact string — "DHS" and "Department of Homeland Security (DHS)" are
  two nodes until vocabulary governance merges them; the atlas makes that authority-control work
  visible. Gray-ish dots include works the collection cites but has not yet tended: the frontier.
  Export a standalone copy with <code>rake enliterator:atlas[FILE]</code>.
</p>
